            title: 'UTM tracking link builder',
            long_description:
                '<h2>What is UTM tracking link builder?</h2>\n<p>A UTM tracking link builder is an online tool designed to help you easily create URLs with UTM parameters. UTM parameters are short text codes you add to a URL that allow you to track where website visitors come from, which specific campaign brought them, and how they interacted with your site.</p>\n<p>You would want to use this tool to accurately measure the performance of your digital marketing efforts across different channels like social media, email, and advertising, making it simple to see what\'s working in your analytics reports.</p>\n\n<h2>How to use UTM tracking link builder</h2>\n<p>Using the UTM tracking link builder is straightforward. Follow these simple steps:</p>\n<ol>\n    <li><b>Enter the Destination URL:</b> Start by pasting the full web address of the page you want to link to (e.g., your homepage, a specific product page, or a landing page) into the designated field.</li>\n    <li><b>Fill in the UTM Parameters:</b> The tool provides fields for key UTM parameters:\n        <ul>\n            <li><b>UTM Source:</b> Enter the source of the traffic (e.g., <code>google</code>, <code>facebook</code>, <code>newsletter</code>).</li>\n            <li><b>UTM Medium:</b> Enter the marketing medium (e.g., <code>cpc</code>, <code>social</code>, <code>email</code>, <code>banner</code>).</li>\n            <li><b>UTM Campaign:</b> Enter the specific campaign name (e.g., <code>summer_sale_2023</code>, <code>q4_promo</code>).</li>\n            <li><b>UTM Term (Optional):</b> Use this for paid search to track keywords (e.g., <code>running+shoes</code>).</li>\n            <li><b>UTM Content (Optional):</b> Use this to differentiate similar content within the same ad or link (e.g., <code>textlink</code>, <code>banner_ad</code>, <code>button_cta</code>).</li>\n        </ul>\n    </li>\n    <li><b>Generate the Link:</b> Once you\'ve filled in the required fields (Source, Medium, Campaign are typically mandatory for good tracking) and any optional ones, click the "Generate" or similar button.</li>\n    <li><b>Copy and Use the Link:</b> The tool will instantly generate the final URL with all the parameters appended. Copy this new, long URL and use it in your marketing campaign.</li>\n</ol>\n<p>When someone clicks this generated link, the UTM parameters are sent to your analytics platform (like Google Analytics), allowing you to attribute that visit and subsequent actions to the specific campaign you created.</p>\n\n<h2>Use cases and applications</h2>\n<p>This UTM builder is incredibly useful for anyone running online marketing campaigns and wanting clear data on performance. Here are a few specific scenarios:</p>\n\n<h3>Tracking Email Campaign Performance</h3>\n<p>When sending out an email newsletter or a promotional email, you can use the builder to create unique tracked links for each button or link within the email. You might set Source=<code>newsletter</code>, Medium=<code>email</code>, and Campaign=<code>[Month]_[Year]_newsletter</code>, plus Content=<code>button_top</code> or <code>textlink_bottom</code> to see which links were most effective.</p>\n\n<h3>Analyzing Social Media Traffic</h3>\n<p>Are you posting links on Facebook, Twitter, or LinkedIn? Use the tool to create specific links for each platform. For a Facebook post, you might use Source=<code>facebook</code>, Medium=<code>social</code>, and Campaign=<code>[Product]_launch</code>. This helps you understand which social platforms drive the most traffic and conversions.</p>\n\n<h3>Measuring Guest Post or Referral Traffic</h3>\n<p>If you write a guest blog post on another website or have partners linking to you, create a specific UTM link. For a guest post on "Blog X", you could use Source=<code>blog_x</code>, Medium=<code>referral</code>, and Campaign=<code>guest_post_[article_topic]</code>. This clearly shows how much traffic that specific external link sends your way.</p>\n\n<h3>Comparing Different Calls to Action (CTAs)</h3>\n<p>On a landing page or in an ad, you might have multiple links or buttons pointing to the same destination. Use the UTM Content parameter to differentiate them. For example, a "Download Now" button might have Content=<code>download_button</code>, while a "Learn More" text link has Content=<code>learn_more_text</code>. This helps you A/B test the effectiveness of different CTAs.</p>\n\n<h2>Benefits and features</h2>\n<p>Using a dedicated UTM tracking link builder offers several advantages:</p>\n<ul>\n    <li><b>Accuracy:</b> Reduces the chance of typos or errors when manually constructing UTM parameters.</li>\n    <li><b>Speed:</b> Generates tracked links instantly, saving you time compared to building them by hand.</li>\n    <li><b>Consistency:</b> Helps maintain a consistent naming convention for your UTM parameters, which is crucial for clean data in your analytics reports.</li>\n    <li><b>Ease of Use:</b> Provides a simple, guided interface for adding all the necessary parameters without needing to remember the exact syntax.</li>\n    <li><b>Improved Analytics:</b> Enables precise tracking of campaign performance, allowing you to make data-driven decisions and optimize your marketing spend.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Start building your tracked links today and unlock better insights into your marketing performance!</p>\n<p>We hope this description helps you understand and use the tool effectively. If you have any questions or suggestions, please feel free to share them!</p>',
